All Types of Keys in DBMS – Complete Interview Guide

(English + Hinglish + Lots of Examples)

Keys are one of the most frequently asked topics in DBMS interviews. They are used to identify records uniquely, establish relationships between tables, and maintain data integrity.

What is a Key?
Interview Definition

A Key is an attribute or a set of attributes that is used to uniquely identify a tuple (row/record) in a table.

Simple English

A key is a unique identifier for each row in a table.

Hinglish

Key ek unique identity card ki tarah hoti hai jo table ke har record ko uniquely identify karti hai.

Real-Life Example

Think of a college.

Student_ID	Name	Phone
101	Lucky	9876543210
102	Rahul	9123456789
103	Aman	9988776655

Many students can have the same name.

But Student_ID is unique.

So Student_ID is a Key.

Why do we need Keys?

Without keys:

Duplicate records can exist.
We cannot uniquely identify records.
Relationships between tables become difficult.
Data integrity cannot be maintained.
Types of Keys

There are 8 major keys commonly asked in interviews.

Super Key
Candidate Key
Primary Key
Alternate Key
Composite (Compound) Key
Foreign Key
Unique Key
Surrogate Key
1. Super Key
Definition

A Super Key is any attribute or combination of attributes that uniquely identifies every row in a table.

It may contain extra attributes.

Example

Employee Table

Emp_ID	Email	Phone	Name
101	a@gmail.com	9876	Lucky
102	b@gmail.com	9988	Rahul

Possible Super Keys:

Emp_ID
Email
Phone
Emp_ID + Name
Emp_ID + Email
Email + Phone
Emp_ID + Phone

All of these uniquely identify employees.

Therefore all are Super Keys.

Important Point

Super Key may have unnecessary attributes.

Example

Emp_ID + Name

Name is unnecessary because Emp_ID alone is enough.

Interview Tip

Every Candidate Key is a Super Key, but every Super Key is NOT a Candidate Key.

2. Candidate Key
Definition

A Candidate Key is the minimum set of attributes that uniquely identifies every record.

No unnecessary attributes.

Example

Employee Table

Emp_ID	Email	Phone
101	a@gmail.com	9876
102	b@gmail.com	9988

Possible Candidate Keys

Emp_ID
Email
Phone

Each alone uniquely identifies the employee.

Not Candidate

Emp_ID + Email

Why?

Because Emp_ID alone is enough.

Extra attribute exists.

Candidate Key Properties

✔ Unique

✔ Minimal

✔ Cannot contain extra attributes

3. Primary Key
Definition

A Primary Key is the Candidate Key chosen to uniquely identify records in a table.

There can be only ONE Primary Key.

Example

Roll_No	Email	Phone

Candidate Keys

Roll_No

Email

Phone

Suppose database designer chooses

Roll_No

Then

Roll_No becomes the Primary Key.

Properties
Unique
Cannot be NULL
Only one Primary Key per table
Interview Question

Can a table have two Primary Keys?

Answer:

❌ No

Only one Primary Key.

4. Alternate Key
Definition

Alternate Keys are Candidate Keys that are not selected as the Primary Key.

Example

Candidate Keys

Roll_No

Email

Phone

Primary Key

Roll_No

Remaining

Email

Phone

These become Alternate Keys.

Memory Trick

Primary = Chosen Candidate

Alternate = Remaining Candidates

5. Composite Key (Compound Key)
Definition

A Composite Key consists of two or more attributes that together uniquely identify a record.

Example

Student Course Table

Student_ID	Course_ID	Marks
101	Java	90
101	Python	95

Student_ID alone?

No.

Course_ID alone?

No.

Together?

Yes.

(Student_ID, Course_ID)

Composite Key.

Real-Life Example

Movie Ticket

Screen_No

Seat_No

Need both.

Another Example

Flight Reservation

Flight_No

Seat_No

Need both.

6. Foreign Key

One of the most important interview questions.

Definition

A Foreign Key is an attribute in one table that refers to the Primary Key of another table.

It creates relationships.

Student Table

Student_ID	Name
101	Lucky

Course Table

Course_ID	Student_ID
Java	101

Student_ID in Course Table

↓

Foreign Key.

Purpose
Maintains Referential Integrity
Connects tables
Interview Question

Can Foreign Key have duplicate values?

✔ Yes

Many students may belong to one department.

Can Foreign Key contain NULL?

✔ Yes

Unless restricted.

7. Unique Key
Definition

A Unique Key ensures that all values in a column are unique, but unlike a Primary Key, it can allow NULL values (database-specific behavior).

Example

Employee

Emp_ID	Email
101	a@gmail.com
102	b@gmail.com

Email

↓

Unique Key.

No duplicate email allowed.

Difference from Primary Key

Primary Key

Unique
No NULL

Unique Key

Unique
NULL may be allowed (depending on the DBMS)
8. Surrogate Key
Definition

A Surrogate Key is an artificial key generated by the system with no business meaning.

Example

Customer Table

Customer_ID	Name
1	Lucky
2	Rahul

Customer_ID

Generated automatically.

It has no business meaning.

Examples

AUTO_INCREMENT (MySQL)
IDENTITY (SQL Server)
SEQUENCE (Oracle, PostgreSQL)

Used because

Names can change.

Phone can change.

Email can change.

But

Customer_ID never changes.

Summary Table
Key	Unique	NULL Allowed	Extra Attributes	Count
Super Key	✔	Depends	✔ Yes	Many
Candidate Key	✔	No	❌ No	Many
Primary Key	✔	❌ No	❌ No	One
Alternate Key	✔	No	❌ No	Many
Composite Key	✔	No	Multiple attributes	One or More
Foreign Key	Not necessarily	✔ Yes	N/A	Many
Unique Key	✔	Usually Yes*	No	Many
Surrogate Key	✔	❌ No	No	Usually One

*Exact NULL behavior depends on the database system.

